00:02:34.260 --> 00:02:35.980
I would have
laughed in your face

00:02:35.980 --> 00:02:39.580
because I was a very, very
reluctant convert to computer

00:02:39.580 --> 00:02:40.920
animation.

00:02:40.920 --> 00:02:45.060
I've always
distrusted computers.

00:02:45.060 --> 00:02:49.850
I was probably the last person
to be dragged backwards,

00:02:49.850 --> 00:02:52.150
with my fingernails
digging into the carpet,

00:02:52.150 --> 00:02:55.790
into CG from hand
drawn animation.

00:02:55.790 --> 00:02:58.580
But the reason I'm here
is because of these two

00:02:58.580 --> 00:03:01.050
crazy kids.

00:03:01.050 --> 00:03:05.160
So that's Ada Lovelace
and Charles Babbage.

00:03:05.160 --> 00:03:08.860
I think a lot of people
know their story roughly

00:03:08.860 --> 00:03:11.580
from computer science 101.

00:03:11.580 --> 00:03:13.595
You kind of get
the quick rundown.

00:03:13.595 --> 00:03:15.730
Charles Babbage, the
[INAUDIBLE] professor

00:03:15.730 --> 00:03:19.395
of mathematics at Cambridge,
the position once held by Newton

00:03:19.395 --> 00:03:22.840
and currently held, I
believe, by Stephen Hawking,

00:03:22.840 --> 00:03:25.910
so he's pretty clever.

00:03:25.910 --> 00:03:29.770
He was famous in
his own time for

00:03:29.770 --> 00:03:31.890
this mysterious
calculating machine

00:03:31.890 --> 00:03:35.510
which was perpetually
planned and never built,

00:03:35.510 --> 00:03:37.540
which we would now
recognize as a computer.

00:03:37.540 --> 00:03:39.730
It is really amazing
their computer,

00:03:39.730 --> 00:03:42.090
as I'll talk about a bit later.

00:03:42.090 --> 00:03:46.860
The other person in that
duo is Ada Lovelace.

00:03:46.860 --> 00:03:50.510
She was born Ada Gordon,
probably better known

00:03:50.510 --> 00:03:54.590
as Ada Gordon, daughter
of George Gordon,

00:03:54.590 --> 00:04:00.030
better known as Lord
Byron, the infamous poet.

00:04:00.030 --> 00:04:05.220
I learned about these people
when I was in a pub in London

00:04:05.220 --> 00:04:08.900
with a friend of mine,
Suw Charman-Anderson, who

00:04:08.900 --> 00:04:11.260
started this thing called
Ada Lovelace Day, which

00:04:11.260 --> 00:04:12.920
you might be familiar with.

00:04:12.920 --> 00:04:15.110
It's sort of an online
blogging festival

00:04:15.110 --> 00:04:17.420
every year to celebrate
women in computing

00:04:17.420 --> 00:04:19.560
and raise their profile.

00:04:19.560 --> 00:04:21.880
And she said to me, Sydney,
you're a woman in tech now.

00:04:21.880 --> 00:04:25.370
You should do a blog post
for Ada Lovelace Day.

00:04:25.370 --> 00:04:28.630
And I said, I don't even
know who Ada Lovelace is.

00:04:28.630 --> 00:04:30.160
I'm also not really
a woman in tech.

00:04:30.160 --> 00:04:31.140
I work on tech.

00:04:31.140 --> 00:04:33.330
I'm not in tech.

00:04:33.330 --> 00:04:36.010
But I went to Wikipedia,
like anybody else would,

00:04:36.010 --> 00:04:40.630
and there I found this
extraordinary story

00:04:40.630 --> 00:04:44.340
about Lovelace, who was
raised by mathematicians so

00:04:44.340 --> 00:04:48.190
that she would not become a
crazy poet like her father.

00:04:48.190 --> 00:04:51.940
It had very much a feel of
a superhero origin story.

00:04:51.940 --> 00:04:55.620
It had that nice, angsty
story of conflict.

00:04:55.620 --> 00:04:58.942
I thought, oh, that would make
a really cute little comic.

00:04:58.942 --> 00:05:00.400
And I thought
because I didn't know

00:05:00.400 --> 00:05:03.940
who Lovelace was that a
nice idea for a blog post

00:05:03.940 --> 00:05:05.690
would just be a
short, little comic.

00:05:05.690 --> 00:05:09.811
I did it as a strip so
it's about this long,

00:05:09.811 --> 00:05:12.310
just explaining who Ada Lovelace
is, and I did it like this.

00:05:15.200 --> 00:05:17.460
So this is all true.

00:05:17.460 --> 00:05:20.670
I can now verify, having read
a hell of a lot of letters--

00:05:20.670 --> 00:05:23.870
sorry, heck of a
lot of letters--

00:05:23.870 --> 00:05:27.870
that Lovelace's mother was
very concerned that she not

00:05:27.870 --> 00:05:30.710
become "poetical,"
which I believe

00:05:30.710 --> 00:05:36.970
was a Victorian euphemism
for not ladylike or wild.

00:05:36.970 --> 00:05:42.500
So she had her tutored
in mathematics and logic.

00:05:42.500 --> 00:05:45.780
She met Babbage at a party in
1833, always the best place

00:05:45.780 --> 00:05:47.000
to meet someone.

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:51.310
He's leaning there on the only
working fragment of a machine

00:05:51.310 --> 00:05:54.310
that he built. That's a
fragment of the difference

00:05:54.310 --> 00:05:56.920
engine, which was a calculator.

00:05:56.920 --> 00:06:01.820
You can actually see that
piece, a beautiful machine

00:06:01.820 --> 00:06:04.480
made of brass, in the
Science Museum in London.

00:06:04.480 --> 00:06:06.160
It's about this big.

00:06:06.160 --> 00:06:09.250
And you could turn a crank
and it could turn out

00:06:09.250 --> 00:06:12.180
some little calculations.

00:06:12.180 --> 00:06:13.710
At this party,
apparently someone

00:06:13.710 --> 00:06:17.300
said, "Has everyone gazed
upon the machine like savages

00:06:17.300 --> 00:06:18.930
looking at a looking glass?"

00:06:18.930 --> 00:06:22.630
Only Ada Byron understood the
true beauty of the machine

00:06:22.630 --> 00:06:24.880
and understand its function.

00:06:24.880 --> 00:06:30.850
She sort of hung out
with Babbage for a while.

00:06:30.850 --> 00:06:33.330
She became very fascinated
with his machine,

00:06:33.330 --> 00:06:37.620
in fact, obsessed with
the analytical engine

00:06:37.620 --> 00:06:40.700
and wrote, of course, a
famous paper about it,

00:06:40.700 --> 00:06:42.525
which I'll talk about in a bit.

00:06:42.525 --> 00:06:44.230
However, this was
a very short comic.

00:06:44.230 --> 00:06:50.410
I should stress the original
comic was maybe four pages long

00:06:50.410 --> 00:06:51.170
laid out.

00:06:51.170 --> 00:06:53.660
And of course, I
reached the end, which

00:06:53.660 --> 00:06:57.600
is a really stupid ending,
said Babbage doesn't build

00:06:57.600 --> 00:07:01.780
his machine and
Lovelace dies at 36

00:07:01.780 --> 00:07:04.120
and it's 100 years before
there's another computer.

00:07:04.120 --> 00:07:06.125
So this was a real dead
end, unfortunately,

00:07:06.125 --> 00:07:08.780
in computing history.

00:07:08.780 --> 00:07:11.984
I think I knocked this whole
comic out in an evening,

00:07:11.984 --> 00:07:14.150
and when I reached this
panel, it was about midnight

00:07:14.150 --> 00:07:17.200
and I thought, ugh, I
can't end it like that.

00:07:17.200 --> 00:07:17.980
That's terrible.

00:07:17.980 --> 00:07:20.480
So I just threw in
as a joke this panel.

00:07:23.880 --> 00:07:28.050
I think I was aware of steampunk
as a thing that existed,

00:07:28.050 --> 00:07:31.320
so I just threw them in fabulous
clothes and gave them ray guns

00:07:31.320 --> 00:07:36.940
and resurrected them
briefly as a punchline.

00:07:36.940 --> 00:07:43.340
I think I was thinking
of "The Avengers."

00:07:43.340 --> 00:07:46.690
It's uncanny.

00:07:46.690 --> 00:07:50.110
So I kind of threw the
comic up online on my blog

00:07:50.110 --> 00:07:53.000
and went to bed, and then
when I woke the next morning,

00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:54.640
it was turning up
all over the internet

00:07:54.640 --> 00:07:58.890
as, "This person is going to do
a comic in which Ada Lovelace

00:07:58.890 --> 00:08:02.340
and Charles Babbage
fight crime."

00:08:02.340 --> 00:08:05.090
It was a joke.

00:08:05.090 --> 00:08:07.680
I succumb easily
to peer pressure,

00:08:07.680 --> 00:08:12.570
and also, I was putting off
working on something else,

00:08:12.570 --> 00:08:15.890
so I started drawing comics
about Ada Lovelace and Charles

00:08:15.890 --> 00:08:18.504
Babbage fighting crime.

00:08:18.504 --> 00:08:20.420
Anyone who's read the
comic will tell you this

00:08:20.420 --> 00:08:25.410
is a very sporadic comic.

00:08:25.410 --> 00:08:26.340
They fight crime.

00:08:26.340 --> 00:08:29.710
They fight it quite badly.

00:08:29.710 --> 00:08:31.480
It's quite a silly
comic I should stress.

00:08:31.480 --> 00:08:35.164
Anyone expecting a very serious
comic about Victorian computing

00:08:35.164 --> 00:08:36.789
is going to be out
of luck because it's

00:08:36.789 --> 00:08:41.200
quite silly, especially because
their chief enemies, of course,

00:08:41.200 --> 00:08:44.410
as they were in life, were
poetry and street music.

00:08:47.390 --> 00:08:50.660
Babbage's famous bugbear
was street music,

00:08:50.660 --> 00:08:53.040
so that's his main
nemesis is the organist.

00:08:56.590 --> 00:09:00.970
Aside from silly comics,
if you look at the book,

00:09:00.970 --> 00:09:04.300
you will notice there's quite a
lot of words in it for a comic.

00:09:04.300 --> 00:09:10.410
This is because as I
was doing the blog,

00:09:10.410 --> 00:09:13.860
I became very
obsessed with reading

00:09:13.860 --> 00:09:15.890
all the wonderful
primary documents that

00:09:15.890 --> 00:09:18.480
were turning up online.

00:09:18.480 --> 00:09:20.590
In a sense, the
footnotes are a joke

00:09:20.590 --> 00:09:23.060
on Lovelace's
famous paper, which

00:09:23.060 --> 00:09:25.390
you can see on Google Books.

00:09:25.390 --> 00:09:28.550
This is it as it
originally appeared.

00:09:28.550 --> 00:09:30.570
Lovelace wrote her paper.

00:09:30.570 --> 00:09:33.220
It began as a translation.

00:09:33.220 --> 00:09:35.000
Babbage himself
never wrote, never

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:41.690
published anything on his own
machine, or anything in detail,

00:09:41.690 --> 00:09:43.460
and of course, women
did not normally

00:09:43.460 --> 00:09:44.750
publish scientific papers.

00:09:44.750 --> 00:09:47.180
This was not something
that was done.

00:09:47.180 --> 00:09:49.100
However, there was
a space for women

00:09:49.100 --> 00:09:54.460
to do translations as sort
of a ladylike accomplishment.

00:09:54.460 --> 00:09:58.000
So when this paper--
this is Menabrea.

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:00.990
He eventually became
prime minister of Italy.

00:10:00.990 --> 00:10:06.210
At the time, he was a guy at a
conference where Babbage spoke

00:10:06.210 --> 00:10:07.510
and described his machine.

00:10:07.510 --> 00:10:09.110
Menabrea took notes.

00:10:09.110 --> 00:10:12.640
He published the
notes in French.

00:10:12.640 --> 00:10:14.850
A year later, Lovelace
translated the notes

00:10:14.850 --> 00:10:18.340
from the French into the English
and begin adding footnotes

00:10:18.340 --> 00:10:20.040
because as she read along.

00:10:20.040 --> 00:10:22.790
She herself was considered an
"expert" on Babbage's machine

00:10:22.790 --> 00:10:27.022
at this time, mostly by
hanging out and continually

00:10:27.022 --> 00:10:28.105
begging him for the plans.

00:10:31.790 --> 00:10:34.231
So she was known as someone
who knew a lot about it.

00:10:34.231 --> 00:10:36.230
That's why she was asked
to translate the paper.

00:10:38.920 --> 00:10:41.130
But as she went down
the translation,

00:10:41.130 --> 00:10:43.250
she began to add
footnotes saying,

00:10:43.250 --> 00:10:45.590
actually, I have a much
clearer illustration of this,

00:10:45.590 --> 00:10:51.440
or in fact, another way
to say this is this.

00:10:51.440 --> 00:10:53.490
A lot, I think to some
extent, she's actually

00:10:53.490 --> 00:10:56.100
writing the footnotes to Babbage
because she often says things

00:10:56.100 --> 00:10:57.960
like, "I don't know
if this has occurred

00:10:57.960 --> 00:10:59.890
to the creator of the
calculating machine,

00:10:59.890 --> 00:11:04.900
but I have this idea about
how this could actually work."

00:11:04.900 --> 00:11:06.400
And this is one of
those notes where

00:11:06.400 --> 00:11:09.730
she says-- this is the first
appearance of general computing

00:11:09.730 --> 00:11:12.690
theory-- "in enabling the
mechanism to combine together

00:11:12.690 --> 00:11:15.910
general symbols in successions
of unlimited variety

00:11:15.910 --> 00:11:18.850
and extent--" she goes on.

00:11:18.850 --> 00:11:21.200
She's Victorian,
so these sentences

00:11:21.200 --> 00:11:23.390
get extremely lengthy.

00:11:23.390 --> 00:11:25.140
If you battle your way
through this paper,

00:11:25.140 --> 00:11:27.740
you'll see it's not the most
readable thing in the world,

00:11:27.740 --> 00:11:31.986
but it is wonderful and it can
be found on Google Books, which

00:11:31.986 --> 00:11:33.360
is my favorite
thing in the world

00:11:33.360 --> 00:11:34.880
and which is why
I'm so delighted

00:11:34.880 --> 00:11:38.500
always to speak to Google
because this entire comic would

00:11:38.500 --> 00:11:43.220
not have been possible without
the incredible cornucopia

00:11:43.220 --> 00:11:48.590
of amazing documents that were
poured out right around 2009

00:11:48.590 --> 00:11:51.700
when I began comic.

00:11:51.700 --> 00:11:54.190
Google Books was
dumping, basically,

00:11:54.190 --> 00:11:59.930
all this 19th century
ephemera online.

00:11:59.930 --> 00:12:02.200
I should stress again
I'm not a proper scholar.

00:12:02.200 --> 00:12:03.640
I'm just some random clown.

00:12:03.640 --> 00:12:05.180
But the great power
of Google Books

00:12:05.180 --> 00:12:10.250
is that I don't have to go
through some specific place

00:12:10.250 --> 00:12:12.240
in an archive and know
what I'm looking for.

00:12:12.240 --> 00:12:16.760
I can just type "Babbage
street music 1830-1870,"

00:12:16.760 --> 00:12:20.290
and you would get
amazing amounts of stuff.

00:12:20.290 --> 00:12:22.981
This is what it
looks like in situ.

00:12:22.981 --> 00:12:26.800
"A Great Calculator, Anecdotes
of the Famous Problem Solver

00:12:26.800 --> 00:12:27.962
Babbage."

00:12:27.962 --> 00:12:29.920
I think the first thing
I was surprised to find

00:12:29.920 --> 00:12:35.120
when I started my research
was how famous Babbage was.

00:12:35.120 --> 00:12:38.650
This was actually from
the Salt Lake City News,

00:12:38.650 --> 00:12:42.270
and Babbage was famous enough
that the Salt Lake City

00:12:42.270 --> 00:12:46.257
News would run some random
anecdotes about him.

00:12:46.257 --> 00:12:48.340
I also like this because
of the "Pocket cigar case

00:12:48.340 --> 00:12:52.975
free to smokers of
Tansills Punch."

00:12:52.975 --> 00:12:54.350
This is a great
set of anecdotes.

00:12:54.350 --> 00:12:58.640
This is in the book, I
believe, and actually, they

00:12:58.640 --> 00:13:00.430
come to some Lovelace
stuff in the end.

00:13:00.430 --> 00:13:04.080
I think she says, "Our family
is an alternate stratification

00:13:04.080 --> 00:13:09.200
of poetry and mathematics"
along the line there.

00:13:09.200 --> 00:13:11.490
Also, to get a sense
of the Victorian era,

00:13:11.490 --> 00:13:13.930
"A clever woman is one whose
ability is never unpleasantly

00:13:13.930 --> 00:13:18.110
felt by the rest of the world."

00:13:18.110 --> 00:13:21.830
So I found just fantastic stuff.

00:13:21.830 --> 00:13:24.600
"This calculating machine was an
endless subject of monologue."

00:13:24.600 --> 00:13:27.390
A lot of people remarked
on Babbage's tendency

00:13:27.390 --> 00:13:29.545
to go on and on about
his calculating machine.

00:13:32.520 --> 00:13:34.035
What else?

00:13:34.035 --> 00:13:38.151
Of course, it wasn't only
Google that I found stuff in.

00:13:38.151 --> 00:13:39.650
The general method
of my approaching

00:13:39.650 --> 00:13:42.720
the comic was I
would run around,

00:13:42.720 --> 00:13:44.610
read a bunch of
primary documents,

00:13:44.610 --> 00:13:47.100
and then just riff on it,
basically, in a comic.

00:13:47.100 --> 00:13:49.380
This is from when Queen
Victoria's diaries were

00:13:49.380 --> 00:13:52.970
digitized and put online.
so of course I immediately

00:13:52.970 --> 00:13:55.839
searched Babbage,
who was, by the way,

00:13:55.839 --> 00:13:58.130
very obsessed with what other
people thought about him.

00:13:58.130 --> 00:14:00.620
He used to keep a scrapbook
with all of his news clippings

00:14:00.620 --> 00:14:02.960
in it.

00:14:02.960 --> 00:14:03.730
And I like this.

00:14:03.730 --> 00:14:06.060
This is a classic
Babbage quotation.

00:14:06.060 --> 00:14:07.930
Lord M-- that's
Lord Melbourne-- has

00:14:07.930 --> 00:14:09.930
said, "Babbage has made
a great fool of himself,

00:14:09.930 --> 00:14:11.890
as he does everywhere."

00:14:11.890 --> 00:14:13.710
Poor old Babbage.

00:14:13.710 --> 00:14:16.930
He had many, many
fantastic talents,

00:14:16.930 --> 00:14:22.110
but he did have some
issues socializing properly

00:14:22.110 --> 00:14:23.890
with people.

00:14:23.890 --> 00:14:27.410
So that's Queen Victoria
on Charles Babbage.

00:14:27.410 --> 00:14:30.900
This is Babbage in Punch
on the Great Exhibition.

00:14:30.900 --> 00:14:33.660
He's very angry at
only being honorably

00:14:33.660 --> 00:14:35.260
mentioned-- "Is that all?

00:14:35.260 --> 00:14:39.620
Scandalous!"-- to go into
the Great Exhibition of 1851.

00:14:39.620 --> 00:14:41.070
He was very angry
that they didn't

00:14:41.070 --> 00:14:43.290
put his calculating
machine in there.

00:14:43.290 --> 00:14:45.890
I think the feeling was
that people would not

00:14:45.890 --> 00:14:48.590
understand what it
was, which I think

00:14:48.590 --> 00:14:53.020
shows a sad underestimation
of the British public.

00:14:53.020 --> 00:14:55.100
I think people would have
thought it was great.

00:14:55.100 --> 00:14:59.800
I like this one, "Babbage, the
logarthmicetical Frankenstein."

00:14:59.800 --> 00:15:03.100
That's from Google Books.

00:15:03.100 --> 00:15:07.490
There's a ton of primary
documents in the book,

00:15:07.490 --> 00:15:10.840
probably too many, apparently.

00:15:10.840 --> 00:15:14.150
This is 1833, The
New York Mirror.

00:15:14.150 --> 00:15:15.980
You need good eyes
to read this one.

00:15:15.980 --> 00:15:16.870
"Oh fie.

00:15:16.870 --> 00:15:19.530
It is said that Ada Byron, sole
daughter of the noble bard,

00:15:19.530 --> 00:15:23.580
is the most coarse and vulgar
woman in England," which

00:15:23.580 --> 00:15:27.680
I do have her swear
a fair bit, so that's

00:15:27.680 --> 00:15:34.890
sourced, if anyone's dubious
about the historical accuracy

00:15:34.890 --> 00:15:36.480
of that.

00:15:36.480 --> 00:15:38.530
You'll notice these
wrong pop-ups here.

00:15:38.530 --> 00:15:39.740
That is also sourced.

00:15:39.740 --> 00:15:43.240
Babbage did, in fact,
invent an error pop-up

00:15:43.240 --> 00:15:46.074
for the analytical
engine, believe it or not.

00:15:46.074 --> 00:15:47.990
"If any mistake had been
made by the attendant

00:15:47.990 --> 00:15:50.270
and a wrong logarithm had
been accidentally given

00:15:50.270 --> 00:15:52.650
to the engine, at
the proper place,

00:15:52.650 --> 00:15:56.430
you'd see a plate above the
logarithm with the word 'wrong'

00:15:56.430 --> 00:15:57.260
engraved on it."

00:15:57.260 --> 00:15:59.749
He later adds the continually
ringing loud bell,

00:15:59.749 --> 00:16:01.915
which I'm sure would be
absolutely delightful if you

00:16:01.915 --> 00:16:03.498
were the attendant
trying to hunt down

00:16:03.498 --> 00:16:06.990
this error in this
gigantic machine.

00:16:06.990 --> 00:16:10.250
So this is Lovelace debugging
one of these error pop-ups

00:16:10.250 --> 00:16:13.200
here with a crowbar, which
is the only way you can

00:16:13.200 --> 00:16:14.550
debug the analytical engine.

00:16:19.060 --> 00:16:21.700
So this just my
joke on the subject.

00:16:21.700 --> 00:16:23.739
"Let's see how Lady
Lovelace is getting on."

00:16:23.739 --> 00:16:25.280
Some cartoon swears
which I won't say

00:16:25.280 --> 00:16:26.571
because this is being recorded.

00:16:28.820 --> 00:16:30.820
"That's a special language
we're developing just

00:16:30.820 --> 00:16:34.720
for the engine."

00:16:34.720 --> 00:16:36.430
Babbage and Lovelace
were actually

00:16:36.430 --> 00:16:37.900
both very funny people.

00:16:37.900 --> 00:16:40.460
People tended to remark
on them as being eccentric

00:16:40.460 --> 00:16:43.082
and tell stories about
how strange they were.

00:16:43.082 --> 00:16:45.290
But amongst all the wonderful
things in Google Books,

00:16:45.290 --> 00:16:47.020
this is by far my favorite.

00:16:47.020 --> 00:16:49.855
This was a really magical
find that would only

00:16:49.855 --> 00:16:52.520
have been possible
with Google Books

00:16:52.520 --> 00:16:55.390
because this is
from a thing called

00:16:55.390 --> 00:16:57.640
the Southern Review, which
was a short lived journal

00:16:57.640 --> 00:16:59.400
out of, I believe, Maryland.

00:17:02.720 --> 00:17:06.417
It was put out in
1867, this is from,

00:17:06.417 --> 00:17:08.000
"to celebrate the
culture of the South

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:11.420
in the wake of the Civil War."

00:17:11.420 --> 00:17:13.099
It reads like a church circular.

00:17:13.099 --> 00:17:17.230
It's clippings from all sorts
of random stuff happening

00:17:17.230 --> 00:17:20.369
around Maryland, generally
speaking, but one of them

00:17:20.369 --> 00:17:24.440
is your basic letter
home to the folks

00:17:24.440 --> 00:17:28.300
from the guy who took
a trip to Europe.

00:17:28.300 --> 00:17:31.340
This is Walter Reed, who is a
wonderful writer, by the way.

00:17:31.340 --> 00:17:32.930
He was actually
from Pennsylvania,

00:17:32.930 --> 00:17:35.660
an English professor
there, and he

00:17:35.660 --> 00:17:39.320
writes by far the most
vivid description of Babbage

00:17:39.320 --> 00:17:41.110
that I found from the period.

00:17:41.110 --> 00:17:44.440
This is actually a
letter from 1854.

00:17:44.440 --> 00:17:45.500
I don't know why.

00:17:45.500 --> 00:17:48.850
I guess they had some space to
fill in the old Southern Review

00:17:48.850 --> 00:17:52.910
10 years later because I'm not
quite sure why they put it in.

00:17:52.910 --> 00:17:56.750
They put in the entire letter,
which is about 13 pages long.

00:17:56.750 --> 00:17:59.910
He meets several people,
but one of them is Babbage,

00:17:59.910 --> 00:18:02.720
and there's just
a magical section.

00:18:02.720 --> 00:18:06.880
This is about two years
after Lovelace had died,

00:18:06.880 --> 00:18:08.630
and we get here,
"After he got up to go,

00:18:08.630 --> 00:18:11.560
by some chance of conversation,
the late Lady Lovelace's name,

00:18:11.560 --> 00:18:13.350
Lord Byron's daughter
Ada, was mentioned.

00:18:13.350 --> 00:18:15.300
He knew her intimately
and spoke highly

00:18:15.300 --> 00:18:18.780
of her mathematical powers
and of her peculiar capability

00:18:18.780 --> 00:18:22.080
higher, he said, then that of
anyone he knew, to prepare,

00:18:22.080 --> 00:18:25.300
I believe it was the
descriptions connected

00:18:25.300 --> 00:18:26.680
with his calculating machine.

00:18:26.680 --> 00:18:28.810
I fear I'm not expressing
myself rightly here

00:18:28.810 --> 00:18:30.959
as to the precise
nature of the subject."

00:18:30.959 --> 00:18:32.750
And I think he's talking
about the programs

00:18:32.750 --> 00:18:37.170
here, the descriptions
of how the machine would

00:18:37.170 --> 00:18:40.020
go through a problem.

00:18:40.020 --> 00:18:43.300
So this is something
that would not

00:18:43.300 --> 00:18:46.490
have been found without
Google search, basically.

00:18:46.490 --> 00:18:49.130
If you were a Babbage
scholar, I can't

00:18:49.130 --> 00:18:50.790
see any conceivable
reason you would

00:18:50.790 --> 00:18:52.998
be reading through every
single issue of the Southern

00:18:52.998 --> 00:18:55.960
Review, 1867.

00:18:55.960 --> 00:18:57.210
So thank you, Google.

00:19:00.110 --> 00:19:01.250
It's just a magical thing.

00:19:04.280 --> 00:19:07.200
The other stream
of research I took

00:19:07.200 --> 00:19:10.500
was regarding the
analytical engine.

00:19:10.500 --> 00:19:13.165
In addition to all these
wonderful primary documents

00:19:13.165 --> 00:19:15.790
that are extremely evocative of
Babbage and Lovelace as people,

00:19:15.790 --> 00:19:18.770
they are extremely
vivid personalities

00:19:18.770 --> 00:19:21.490
and they write all
their own material.

00:19:21.490 --> 00:19:25.310
They come up with great gags for
themselves and great dialogue.

00:19:25.310 --> 00:19:28.340
But there's sort of a third
character in the comic,

00:19:28.340 --> 00:19:31.340
and that was always
the analytical engine.

00:19:31.340 --> 00:19:36.920
As I said, I'm not
a computer person,

00:19:36.920 --> 00:19:39.190
so for me, when I tended
to draw the engine,

00:19:39.190 --> 00:19:45.530
it's this vast, building
sized labyrinth of confusion.

00:19:45.530 --> 00:19:48.070
People tend to get lost
and attacked in it.

00:19:48.070 --> 00:19:50.780
But I guess as I was
drawing the comic,

00:19:50.780 --> 00:19:54.100
I began being really
frustrated by the fact

00:19:54.100 --> 00:19:57.240
that pretty much every
book, even fairly

00:19:57.240 --> 00:20:02.380
specialist books on the engine,
would, A, say it was exactly

00:20:02.380 --> 00:20:04.760
like a modern computer but
it's too complicated for you

00:20:04.760 --> 00:20:06.800
to understand it.

00:20:06.800 --> 00:20:11.650
And also, they wouldn't give me
a drawing of the engine, which

00:20:11.650 --> 00:20:13.230
really, as a comic
artist, I want

00:20:13.230 --> 00:20:20.337
to see a drawing of a huge
ass engine made of cogs.

00:20:20.337 --> 00:20:21.170
It's just eye candy.

00:20:24.840 --> 00:20:27.530
I had to actually
make one myself

00:20:27.530 --> 00:20:31.247
so you can get a sense
of what this engine was.

00:20:31.247 --> 00:20:32.330
A lot of you are familiar.

00:20:32.330 --> 00:20:34.871
Sorry, this is my own video,
and I know I shot it like a noob

00:20:34.871 --> 00:20:37.800
in portrait.

00:20:37.800 --> 00:20:41.180
So this is the beautiful--
let me turn on the sound

00:20:41.180 --> 00:20:43.112
because you have to hear it.

00:20:43.112 --> 00:20:47.060
This is the difference
engine that they've built

00:20:47.060 --> 00:20:48.750
in Mountain View, California.

00:20:48.750 --> 00:20:51.361
This is them demonstrating
it for me, which

00:20:51.361 --> 00:20:52.580
was just wonderful of them.

00:20:52.580 --> 00:20:57.455
You can hear me oohing and
aahing like an idiot over it.

00:21:00.268 --> 00:21:02.559
Those beautiful arms at the
back are carrying the ones.

00:21:07.940 --> 00:21:09.500
So that's the difference engine.

00:21:09.500 --> 00:21:12.150
It's a huge machine and
it's incredibly beautiful

00:21:12.150 --> 00:21:15.251
and incredibly
clever, but that's not

00:21:15.251 --> 00:21:17.000
the analytical engine.

00:21:17.000 --> 00:21:21.210
There's two machines of
Babbage, the difference engine

00:21:21.210 --> 00:21:23.480
and the analytical engine.

00:21:23.480 --> 00:21:27.080
The difference engine
is essentially an adder.

00:21:27.080 --> 00:21:28.500
It really only adds.

00:21:28.500 --> 00:21:32.150
It adds in a very specific
way and a very clever way,

00:21:32.150 --> 00:21:34.610
but it can only add.

00:21:34.610 --> 00:21:39.140
Right around the early
1830s, pretty much

00:21:39.140 --> 00:21:44.310
when Babbage met Lovelace,
he began to think,

00:21:44.310 --> 00:21:47.070
what if you could
take the sum that

00:21:47.070 --> 00:21:48.770
came out of one
end of the engine

00:21:48.770 --> 00:21:51.120
and put it back
in the other end?

00:21:51.120 --> 00:21:55.550
He described this as the
engine eating its own tail.

00:21:55.550 --> 00:22:01.620
So he devised a second
machine, the analytical engine.

00:22:01.620 --> 00:22:07.320
He didn't build either of
them, partly because it's just

00:22:07.320 --> 00:22:08.310
really super hard.

00:22:08.310 --> 00:22:10.050
I think a lot of
people asked me,

00:22:10.050 --> 00:22:13.570
why didn't Babbage build
the analytical engine?

00:22:13.570 --> 00:22:15.290
It's actually really,
really, really hard

00:22:15.290 --> 00:22:19.140
to build a giant computer
entirely made of cogs.

00:22:19.140 --> 00:22:22.470
It's not a disgrace
not to complete it.

00:22:22.470 --> 00:22:25.060
Babbage also kept
changing the plans.

00:22:25.060 --> 00:22:27.305
So this is the famous Plan 25.

00:22:30.010 --> 00:22:32.079
It's the most beautiful
and the most complete

00:22:32.079 --> 00:22:32.870
of Babbage's plans.

00:22:32.870 --> 00:22:34.970
This is from 1840, so
this is the machine

00:22:34.970 --> 00:22:40.330
that Lovelace would have
been writing her paper about.

00:22:40.330 --> 00:22:46.110
So at first, as a comic
artist who is not very clever,

00:22:46.110 --> 00:22:49.570
I looked at this picture and
said, ooh, and then I said,

00:22:49.570 --> 00:22:52.420
I have no idea what
I'm looking at here.

00:22:52.420 --> 00:22:56.610
So in order to draw
the machine accurately,

00:22:56.610 --> 00:22:58.360
I had to basically
go in and start

00:22:58.360 --> 00:23:02.350
doing elevations and hunt down
as many of Babbage's diagrams

00:23:02.350 --> 00:23:03.860
as I could.

00:23:03.860 --> 00:23:07.750
It was by no means
straightforward to do

00:23:07.750 --> 00:23:14.120
an image of this,
partly because Babbage

00:23:14.120 --> 00:23:19.870
wasn't very good at showing
complete elevations.

00:23:19.870 --> 00:23:23.700
So this is very much an
interpretation of me,

00:23:23.700 --> 00:23:29.096
but anyway, this is possibly
the first visualization

00:23:29.096 --> 00:23:29.970
of the entire engine.

00:23:34.020 --> 00:23:37.991
You may go "ooh" because
it took me forever.

00:23:37.991 --> 00:23:38.490
Thank you.

00:23:38.490 --> 00:23:42.147
Thank you very much.

00:23:42.147 --> 00:23:43.730
There's the punch
cards at the bottom.

00:23:43.730 --> 00:23:47.170
I'll actually show
you in animation

00:23:47.170 --> 00:23:49.860
how I believe it works
because it's much clearer.

00:23:49.860 --> 00:23:51.330
There's a lot going on.

00:23:51.330 --> 00:23:55.300
Basically, you have storage
going down the back here.

00:23:55.300 --> 00:23:57.880
This is a whole line of gears.

00:23:57.880 --> 00:24:02.380
For Babbage, this
machine was exclusively

00:24:02.380 --> 00:24:03.730
a machine for doing arithmetic.

00:24:03.730 --> 00:24:08.150
The entire bulk of this
thing is numerical.

00:24:08.150 --> 00:24:11.790
So each of these columns
represent a number

00:24:11.790 --> 00:24:14.060
with 50 decimal places.

00:24:14.060 --> 00:24:18.120
So each little gear has a number
from one to 10, its decimal,

00:24:18.120 --> 00:24:18.920
on it.

00:24:18.920 --> 00:24:21.160
So you set this to 5,
this to 2, and then

00:24:21.160 --> 00:24:24.200
you have 25, this
to 3, you have 325.

00:24:24.200 --> 00:24:25.600
So it just goes up.

00:24:25.600 --> 00:24:28.140
And so if you have a
column of 50 gears,

00:24:28.140 --> 00:24:31.540
it's a column of a number
of 50 decimal places.

00:24:31.540 --> 00:24:34.270
50 is a lot of decimal places.

00:24:34.270 --> 00:24:38.970
Babbage said himself that
the reason he put in so many

00:24:38.970 --> 00:24:40.880
is that he thought
that should "be

00:24:40.880 --> 00:24:45.400
sufficient for all future
purposes of science."

00:24:45.400 --> 00:24:48.080
That's Babbage all over for you.

00:24:48.080 --> 00:24:51.370
So here's the three
types of punch cards

00:24:51.370 --> 00:24:53.800
that I'll go through
in a bit, barrels.

00:24:53.800 --> 00:24:57.105
I should say I think the
machine was probably actually

00:24:57.105 --> 00:24:59.770
a bit taller than this.

00:24:59.770 --> 00:25:02.240
Cats for scale.

00:25:02.240 --> 00:25:05.310
I think also it's very likely
it could have been freestanding.

00:25:05.310 --> 00:25:07.030
I think you would
have had to have

00:25:07.030 --> 00:25:10.950
enmeshed the entire
thing in an enormous cage

00:25:10.950 --> 00:25:12.790
to keep it stable.

00:25:12.790 --> 00:25:18.030
The whole machine is based
around numerical gears that

00:25:18.030 --> 00:25:20.745
turn around and they have
locks to hold it in place,

00:25:20.745 --> 00:25:23.610
and if the lock hits
a tooth at any point

00:25:23.610 --> 00:25:27.400
in this gigantic machine,
the whole thing will freeze.

00:25:27.400 --> 00:25:30.040
So absolutely nothing
can be out of alignment

00:25:30.040 --> 00:25:32.060
by so much as a
couple of millimeters,

00:25:32.060 --> 00:25:34.630
so stability would be
a big, big, big issue

00:25:34.630 --> 00:25:35.620
with this machine.

00:25:35.620 --> 00:25:37.370
Although, that said,
the difference engine

00:25:37.370 --> 00:25:39.880
works on that same principle,
and generally speaking,

00:25:39.880 --> 00:25:43.662
it hardly ever crashes ever.

00:25:43.662 --> 00:25:45.566
AUDIENCE: Do replicas
of the [INAUDIBLE]?

00:25:48.192 --> 00:25:48.900
SYDNEY PADUA: No.

00:25:48.900 --> 00:25:53.510
They think there are only 20,
so you have a little more space

00:25:53.510 --> 00:25:57.010
for error in those.

00:25:57.010 --> 00:26:00.330
So that's the analytical engine.

00:26:00.330 --> 00:26:03.850
So in the book, without
the power of animation,

00:26:03.850 --> 00:26:05.710
this is the plan I did.

00:26:05.710 --> 00:26:10.600
It's actually quite a bit
more clear in animation.

00:26:10.600 --> 00:26:13.550
I had a great
advantage in building

00:26:13.550 --> 00:26:15.760
these diagrams in that I
am a computer animator,

00:26:15.760 --> 00:26:19.510
so I work on this
thing all day long.

00:26:19.510 --> 00:26:21.870
So this is a simplification.

00:26:21.870 --> 00:26:24.700
This is sort of a
cartoon engine version

00:26:24.700 --> 00:26:27.430
that's stripped down,
partly because it's

00:26:27.430 --> 00:26:31.820
really difficult to see
what's going on when you have

00:26:31.820 --> 00:26:34.810
the whole thing in,
and also, it's so huge,

00:26:34.810 --> 00:26:37.690
so you have helpfully labeled
the layer "whole thing."

00:26:37.690 --> 00:26:39.960
It's so huge my
machine really starts

00:26:39.960 --> 00:26:43.860
to struggle once you
put in all those gears,

00:26:43.860 --> 00:26:46.610
but it's just decimal places.

00:26:46.610 --> 00:26:49.370
So this is actually just a
slice, and each slice going up

00:26:49.370 --> 00:26:51.170
is exactly the
same, so you don't

00:26:51.170 --> 00:26:55.090
need all those 50 to understand
the information flow.

00:26:55.090 --> 00:26:56.485
So here's your engine.

00:26:56.485 --> 00:26:58.360
I'm assuming you guys
are interested in this,

00:26:58.360 --> 00:26:59.361
because [INAUDIBLE].

00:27:03.510 --> 00:27:05.135
Some people start
to glaze over, but I

00:27:05.135 --> 00:27:08.910
thought Google would
probably be into it.

00:27:08.910 --> 00:27:13.110
So just so I can explain here,
basically, the red colors

00:27:13.110 --> 00:27:15.885
indicate the driver and
the greens are passive.

00:27:20.800 --> 00:27:24.240
So the first thing that
activates is the number card,

00:27:24.240 --> 00:27:28.370
and that will be a card
with each 50 decimal number

00:27:28.370 --> 00:27:31.580
in holes, basically, or
rather, a lack of holes.

00:27:31.580 --> 00:27:34.180
The way these punch
card things work,

00:27:34.180 --> 00:27:35.930
so you have a whole
arrangement of levers,

00:27:35.930 --> 00:27:39.200
each lined up to all the holes.

00:27:39.200 --> 00:27:40.930
You'll have a hole
pretty much everywhere

00:27:40.930 --> 00:27:43.070
except for one point.

00:27:43.070 --> 00:27:47.457
So as the card is pushed over
the levers, if there's holes,

00:27:47.457 --> 00:27:49.290
it just goes right
through, nothing happens,

00:27:49.290 --> 00:27:51.180
but if there's no
hole, then the card

00:27:51.180 --> 00:27:54.070
will push the lever at that
corresponding position,

00:27:54.070 --> 00:27:57.330
so that's how the
punch cards work.

00:27:57.330 --> 00:28:00.510
So that will basically
select a bunch of levers,

00:28:00.510 --> 00:28:02.170
50 of them-- I
haven't animated 50

