00:45:12.280 --> 00:45:14.510
but was it, in fact,
an anomaly for there

00:45:14.510 --> 00:45:16.105
to be a woman mathematician?

00:45:16.105 --> 00:45:19.950
Was she seen of
some sort of oddity?

00:45:19.950 --> 00:45:22.450
SYDNEY PADUA: I mean, people
tend to see it as cute,

00:45:22.450 --> 00:45:24.550
to be honest.

00:45:24.550 --> 00:45:28.720
They tend to write, oh,
isn't that adorable, a woman

00:45:28.720 --> 00:45:30.180
trying to do mathematics?

00:45:30.180 --> 00:45:34.860
The letter about mathematics
damaging a woman's constitution

00:45:34.860 --> 00:45:39.800
is actually from Augustus De
Morgan, who wrote to her mother

00:45:39.800 --> 00:45:42.300
twice, apparently, saying,
I'm very, very concerned

00:45:42.300 --> 00:45:46.990
because Lady Lovelace has
as much mathematical power

00:45:46.990 --> 00:45:49.180
as would challenge the
constitution of a man,

00:45:49.180 --> 00:45:53.140
and somehow he felt
that it was over

00:45:53.140 --> 00:45:55.120
clocked for a woman's body.

00:45:55.120 --> 00:45:57.820
I mean, this was actually
a very common idea.

00:46:00.430 --> 00:46:02.490
He gave me some
great comic dialogue.

00:46:02.490 --> 00:46:06.200
He said, "Soon, the struggle
between body and mind

00:46:06.200 --> 00:46:09.010
will begin."

00:46:09.010 --> 00:46:12.410
It's actually incredibly sad
and ironic because the idea was

00:46:12.410 --> 00:46:17.200
that mathematics, this excessive
use of that part of the brain,

00:46:17.200 --> 00:46:20.260
would specifically
damage women's wombs,

00:46:20.260 --> 00:46:25.340
and Lovelace did, in fact,
die of uterine cancer.

00:46:25.340 --> 00:46:28.050
I can't find anyone
using that as proof.

00:46:28.050 --> 00:46:31.030
I'm sure somebody
somewhere said, I told you.

00:46:31.030 --> 00:46:38.780
And actually, Lovelace's
mentor was Mary Somerville,

00:46:38.780 --> 00:46:41.070
after whom Somerville
College in Oxford is named.

00:46:41.070 --> 00:46:43.199
She did all these very
complicated translations

00:46:43.199 --> 00:46:45.240
of works from the continent,
and Lovelace is very

00:46:45.240 --> 00:46:47.510
definitely modeling
herself on Somerville

00:46:47.510 --> 00:46:52.180
in doing the translation of
the analytical engine paper.

00:46:52.180 --> 00:46:55.024
But Somerville had
to study in secret

00:46:55.024 --> 00:46:56.565
because her parents
thought she would

00:46:56.565 --> 00:46:59.680
hurt herself studying math.

00:46:59.680 --> 00:47:02.490
I think her first husband didn't
agree with her studying math,

00:47:02.490 --> 00:47:04.660
so she wrote her first
mathematics books

00:47:04.660 --> 00:47:07.780
when she was 45 when he died.

00:47:07.780 --> 00:47:09.490
That's when she got
her first freedom.

00:47:09.490 --> 00:47:12.660
So no, it was
very, very unusual.

00:47:12.660 --> 00:47:16.740
Lovelace is kind of at
the end of that era.

00:47:16.740 --> 00:47:20.700
They started to have
women's programs in college

00:47:20.700 --> 00:47:23.120
in the 1870s, 1880s,
and I think that's when

00:47:23.120 --> 00:47:25.554
it started to turn around.

